---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description="About Ismail El Jamiy — PhD candidate in AI, engineer, and photographer from Casablanca, based in Toulouse.">

  <article class="page-container">

    <header class="page-header">
      <div class="page-eyebrow">Ismail El Jamiy</div>
      <h1 class="page-title">About</h1>
      <div class="page-rule-short" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    </header>

    <div class="prose">

      <p class="drop-cap">
        It started with a computer. I was young, fascinated by what this machine could actually
        do — not just run programs someone else wrote, but be shaped, instructed, made to think.
        That curiosity pulled me toward coding, then toward machine learning, then toward computer
        vision, which consumed me for the better part of two years. When I started mixing it with
        language models, something clicked: I had found the intersection where I wanted to work.
        That intersection is now my PhD.
      </p>

      <p>
        I'm a PhD candidate in Artificial Intelligence at the University of Toulouse
        (IRIT / IMT / CLLE), working at the crossroads of computer vision and large language
        models — specifically applied to the automatic recognition of handwritten text in medieval
        Arabic scientific manuscripts. It feels like home in every sense: Arabic is my mother
        tongue, and the manuscripts I work with carry centuries of Islamic scholarship in
        mathematics, astronomy, and medicine. Making them machine-readable means making them
        accessible to researchers everywhere.
      </p>

      <div class="ornament-divider" aria-hidden="true"><span>✦</span></div>
      <h2>Background</h2>
      <p>
        I'm Moroccan, from Casablanca. I completed my baccalauréat in Mathematical Sciences,
        then joined the École Nationale Supérieure d'Arts et Métiers (ENSAM Casablanca),
        where I specialised in AI and Computer Science. My final year brought me to Toulouse
        for an internship at IRIT, working on few-shot medical image segmentation with
        meta-learning — and I never quite left. The same lab, a different team, and now a PhD.
      </p>
      <p>
        Before Toulouse I also worked on computer vision for insurance claims at SYGMA.AI and
        on PPE detection for industrial safety at Lesieur Cristal — two very different domains
        that sharpened my instinct for applied, real-world problems.
      </p>

      <div class="ornament-divider" aria-hidden="true"><span>✦</span></div>
      <h2>Research</h2>
      <p>
        My PhD combines two genuinely hard challenges: handwritten text recognition (HTR) in
        degraded historical documents, and the specificities of classical Arabic — a cursive,
        context-dependent script with rich morphology written by hands separated by centuries.
        The manuscripts I work with are held in collections across Morocco, Algeria, and Europe.
      </p>
      <p>
        Beyond recognition, I am building dedicated language models trained on the recognised
        text — models that understand the vocabulary, grammar, and semantic patterns of medieval
        Arabic scientific prose. Think of it as a specialised AI collaborator for historians of science.
      </p>

      <div class="ornament-divider" aria-hidden="true"><span>✦</span></div>
      <h2>Beyond the lab</h2>
      <p>
        I photograph — with my phone, deliberately. What draws me is not technical perfection
        but the moment: an emotion caught off guard, a shaft of light through a narrow medina
        street, the geometry of a facade I wasn't expecting. Architecture is something I find
        endlessly interesting, especially the medieval kind — the weight and proportion of
        Gothic vaults, the ornament of Andalusian tile-work, the logic that holds a Renaissance
        dome together.
      </p>
      <p>
        Outside of that: gym, running when the weather allows, a lot of films and series and
        anime, story-driven video games (the kind where the writing matters), and music — if it
        sounds good, I listen to it. Genre is irrelevant.
      </p>

      <div class="ornament-divider" aria-hidden="true"><span>✦</span></div>
      <h2>Languages</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Arabic</strong> — Native</li>
        <li><strong>French</strong> — Bilingual (TCF C1, score 543)</li>
        <li><strong>English</strong> — Advanced</li>
      </ul>

    </div>

  </article>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page-container {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 4rem 1.5rem 5rem;
  }

  .page-header {
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }

  .page-title {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 4vw, 2.75rem);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--fg);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  /* ── Prose ────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .prose {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--fg);
  }

  .prose p {
    margin-bottom: 1.4em;
  }

  .prose h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.4rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-olive);
    margin: 2.5rem 0 0.75rem;
  }

  .prose ul {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin-bottom: 1.4em;
  }

  .prose ul li {
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: 0.4em;
  }

  .prose ul li::before {
    content: "—";
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-terracotta);
  }

  /* Drop cap on first paragraph */
  .drop-cap::first-letter {
    font-size: 4.5em;
    line-height: 0.78;
    float: left;
    margin-right: 0.08em;
    color: var(--color-terracotta);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
  }
</style>
